<br>
Creapiing walked through the dark alleys, pondering the simple beauty of the shadowed patterns cast on the streets by dark lights. A familiar voice wafted through an open window. -Hatred, like my sabre, must be directed like a tool. It must be guided,directed, shaped and implemented.-<br>
She stood still a moment and then moved on.<br>
<br>
How like House T'Rhennic to so eloquently word her own ideals. Hate, when acknoledged, is endless strength. And yet, as she had explained to many of the Prejudiced light lovers, she did not hate everything. Hate was a tool, and hate can become a focus to give one advantage over any enemy. Many lightlovers rejected the idea that they had hatred within them. Innoruuk calls the Teir'dal to recognize their own hate and to use it for their strength.<br>
<br>
Undoubtedly, Innorruk did not look favorably upon those who indulged in hated and rage for its own sake. This path was blind in its own way. Unfocused hate or rage was a weakness, just as denying ones own hate was weakness.<br>
<br>
Perhaps Zressoth would be a good person to charge to teach the new seeds the nature of hatred, for the House T'Rhennic had more to offer than the simple blood of battle.<br>
<br>
Creapiing V'Etch <br>
